# Feature Workflow (lightweight, owner-driven)

How we build here. Requirements come from the **owner in chat** ({{adjust if tickets/FRDs are used}}).
Be pragmatic; don't add ceremony. Run the phases in order; don't skip verify + KB-sync.

> Golden rules: ground in the KB before coding · keep the app shippable after each slice · the gate is
> {{GATE}} + a real check · update the KB in the same change · {{push policy}} · never touch secrets.

## 1. Capture
Log the requirement (dated) in the knowledge base before implementing, so intent is never lost.

**Large/multi-module initiatives:** after logging to the changelog, also consolidate the requirement
into its **FRD** under `knowledgebase/frds/` (create one from the template if the module has none).
Mature the FRD with the owner (Draft → In Review → Approved); only an **Approved** FRD is promoted to a
plan and built. See `frds/README.md`. (Small Tier-1 changes skip FRDs — changelog + build.)

## 2. Ground
Read the relevant KB docs + the code you'll touch. **Reuse** existing helpers/services. For a large
or uncertain change, spawn the **context-gatherer** agent first.

## 3. Decide
Resolve ambiguities yourself; record notable choices. **Ask the owner only** when a choice is
irreversible/costly, expands scope, conflicts with a prior requirement, or needs a secret.

## 4. Implement (small slices)
{{Project structure rule — thin routes/UI, logic in the right layer. New data → migration with
access-control in the same change.}}

## 5. Self-test
Type-check → build → {{GATE}}. Add/adjust tests for new behaviour. Loop until green.

## 6. Validate with subagents (non-trivial changes)
Spawn in parallel: **security-reviewer**, **quality-reviewer**, and for milestones **professional-qa**.
Also run any built-in code/security review. Fix clear gaps; ask the owner about scope expansions.

## 7. Verify for real
{{How to actually exercise the change (drive the UI / hit the API / inspect output) and read the result.}}

## 8. Sync the knowledge base
Update the database index (on schema change) + the relevant **`knowledgebase/modules/<module>`** doc
(fold in the durable "how it works now") + the requirements log — in the **same** change as the code.
If the change came from an FRD, leave the FRD as the requirements-of-record and move its knowledge into
the module doc.

## 9. Commit (+ push when asked)
Commit per slice with a clear message. {{Push/PR policy.}}

## Optional: bigger initiatives
For a multi-step initiative worth tracking, drop a short note folder under `.claude/plans/` (see its
README). Optional and lightweight — most chat-sized requests don't need it.
